And methodArn we get from `  const {
    methodArn
  } = event;`  (event from lambda)

You can skip the `          {
            organizationId,
            profileId: authClaims.sub,
          }` in generateAllow(), It's data we want when that socket connection trigger other lambdas.

```
const generateAllow = (principalId, resource, claims) => generatePolicy(
  principalId,
  'Allow',
  resource,
  claims
);

const generatePolicy = (principalId, effect, resource, claims) => {
  const authResponse = {};
  authResponse.principalId = principalId;
  if (effect && resource) {
    const policyDocument = {};
    policyDocument.Version = '2012-10-17'; // default version
    policyDocument.Statement = [];
    const statementOne = {};
    statementOne.Action = 'execute-api:Invoke'; // default action
    statementOne.Effect = effect;
    statementOne.Resource = resource;
    policyDocument.Statement[0] = statementOne;
    authResponse.policyDocument = policyDocument;
  }
  authResponse.context = claims;
  return authResponse;
};


```

Hope it solves your problem

@boazdejong I think the reason is, that you fetch them in your plugin's constructor. The constructor should only setup the hooks and commands of the plugin, but not access this.serverless.service at that time.

You would do the validation and evaluation of you plugin's configuration at a `validate` method, that you call from the very first location within your hooks. That's the only location, where it is guaranteed that the service has been setup correctly.

Please also check other plugins, for how they work or some of the internal plugins.
